Capt. Hector's Log book. November 19th, 1887:

A haze of blood and gunfire. Screams and imprecations. A man I knew with my knife in his heart. Rather quickly, it's over. I'm drenched in blood and racked with wounds, and many of my crew are dead - but I stand victorious. Push the corpses of the mutineers into the sea, and press on. I swear to god that the ghastly sight of the blood-drenched deck and the pungent smell will haunt my dreams till the day I give my body to the Zee.

There, in the distance, the light of safety; Fallen London. We're home, we survived, we're victorious. The crew shouts in joy, and I followed suit. My face feels wet.

When does victory feels so hollow now?

I prayed to Salt, Storm, and Stone that I will survive this voyage, for the deep dark zee is unforgiving.
